<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-314-262  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 314 262.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  May 29 1989 n250 p28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bypass vendor signs users. (Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schultz, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc gives users an alternative to thestringent prices and services of local Bell companies.andP;  Thecompany has laid fiber in different parts of the country, blazingfiber optic network trails.andP;  MFS supplies one of its firstcustomers with a DS-3 connection that comes from the centraloffice to an MFS hub.andP;  The 45M-bps connection is split at the hub.andO;Sixteen T1 spans make their way to two separate downtownbuildings.andP;  Incoming and outgoing WATS calls are placed via theMFS network.andP;  Companies are saving money by bypassing Bellcompanies.andP;  In addition, some companies feel that MFS is moreflexible than the local Bell companies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc. (products).andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsNetworksCompetitionGrowthTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>